text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Dami Okes comment on this

Im not cracked. 

Nor do I actually want to be. 


The truth is, Im here by complete accident. 

Six months ago, I started to go down a rabbit hole.

I was curious why the music industry wasnt paying attention to the education space in music tech. 

I wanted change after so many friends were frustrated scavenging for resources to learn music production. 

I knew we could change that. 

I had no idea how. 

The past six months, I doubled down on obsessions: music tech, startups, and learning how people learn. 

I chatted with producers, re-analyzed my workflows in Ableton, and finally learned what PMF stood for. 

Every obsession became Virtuoso, and that made me more addicted to this whole process.

Still, Im not trying to build the next unicorn, get into a prestigious accelerator, or even want to be a Linkedin top voice. 

Im here because of a problem 3 million producers face that an industry stays silent on, and I know were the only ones that can solve it. 

Im not here to be cracked. 

Im here for the love of the game. 

Launchmas #22

i just got penetrated


by a Cactus (YC S25)


working at cactus means voluntarily running into sharp things every day

over the past few weeks, ive been cold emailing, following up, building databases, and penetrating directly into the networks at 130+ universities including ivies and other schools that definitely did not want a 16 year old touching their inbox

this isnt glamorous work
its getting left on read
its just circling back for the 4th time
its manually cleaning data at 3:33am wondering why you didnt choose a softer plant

but every now and then, penetration successful
a reply
a call
a real relationship

and suddenly the cactus doesnt feel like punishment
it feels like training

lesson learned:
growth is spiky
progress hurts a little
and if youre not getting penetrated by resistance, youre probably not pushing hard enough

very grateful for cactus 
very grateful for the scars
and very excited about what were building

if your job hasnt emotionally penetrated you yet
You not even working

ty goat Aadi V. for helping me penetrate the engagement metrics

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Alex Yis comment on this

Startups are built like musical scales.

Were building ours in chords. 


Not traditional linear pathways, but finding harmony within constraints. 

Thats exactly what our MVP taught us, and keeps teaching us. 

Building in Ohio, we had no idea what the usual startup playbook was. I learned what a coffee chat is when my friend described theirs two months ago. 

So we learned to play with the cards weve been dealt: 

- Locally hosting LLMs because API costs wouldve killed us.
- Testing with the same community we built through our music production club.
- Growing on LinkedIn to expose the problem to the people who could actually help us solve it. 

Every constraint forced us to get creative. Every limitation became a feature. 

Thats when I realized: dont raise. 

Not yet. 

Not until youve exhausted every resource around you. 

Fundraising is the easy answer. Building with constraints is the hard one. 

But the hard ones teach you what your product actually needs to be. 

That being said, this chapter is about to close. 

Our MVP is coming. Weve proven the thesis with almost nothing.

Now its time to scale what works. 

Were officially raising in 2026. 

If youre building right now and think you need to raise to make progress, take a moment to reflect.

Exhaust your constraints first. They'll teach you more than capital ever could.

Launchmas #23

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Noah Ricks comment on this

Cincinnati is not the next SF 


Its different, and the core reason lies in its DNA. 

San Francisco is the gold rush city. You have to be constantly innovating to survive. 

High risk, high reward.

Cincinnati is all about first principles, home to giants like Procter & Gamble and GE. 

Its grounded in the grind.

Now youd think that bringing startup culture to the Queen City would end up failing miserably. 

But theres little pockets of startups EVERYWHERE. 

From StartupCincy to Cintrifuse Capital to the 1819 Innovation Hub, there are communities, VCs, and accelerators thriving in every neighborhood. 

And as a high school founder, I had no idea. 

The thing is, Cincinnati is missing something that first principles wont tell you: the best ideas are where you least expect them to be. 

Im a believer in that as a music tech founder. Virtuoso isnt anything that people expect. 

But the Mason Venture Studio confirmed that belief for me.

7 startups, all high school students, all following the Queen City approach: ground yourself in first principles, then ship fast. 

You wouldnt expect that. 

No one would. 

As a city, we need to understand our foundations, but not let them define us. 

We need to expect the unexpected, ground ourselves in what makes us unique, and build in public. 

One community. One city. Strength in Unity. 

Thats how we build.

If youre a founder or investor in Cincinnati, lets connect. Theres so much to come in 2026. 

Launchmas #21

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Aadi V.s comment on this

Most people my age are worried about homework.

Im 12, and Im playing a very different game.


Hey everyone, Im Ritvik.

Im a 12 y/o  who somehow ended up building Taskflows (taskflows.net) and Linktern (linktern.org is still under development) , which are platforms now used by thousands of students across 50+ countries. Along the way, Ive published 150+ research articles read by 320,000+ people, represented my country internationally in mathematical olympiads, landed tech and research internships, and grown a community of 4,500+ followers here on LinkedIn.

This might sound impressive, but NONE of it was planned.

At the start of 2025, I was lowkey just an average 12 year old kid. All I did was schoolwork, homework, and trying to learn how to code from Mosh Hamedani tutorials on Youtube.

Before LinkedIn, my world was mostly math olympiads and a little bit of research. 

But when I first discovered LinkedIn, I DEFINITELY didnt plan to post here at first. Nobody does. I thought LinkedIn was only for professional stuff like jobs and internships, so I usually just scrolled and read what other ppl were doing.

Pretty soon, I built up the confidence and started sharing what I was building. A LOT of posts flopped...but a few of them blew up. People started engaging with my posts, commenting, giving feedback, and eventually I went from sending out tons of connection requests to receiving them.

In 2026, Ill be sharing MUCH MORE of what Im doing, what Im learning, and what works and doesnt

If youre reading this, Id love to know you.

What are you working on right now?

Youre reading stories while Im writing them



That was my motto for the last four years, and during them, I wouldnt want to get caught dead with a book in my hands.

Now, though, Im back to the books. Im reading stories and writing them.

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Chase Hawkins comment on this

Bwoah. 

Stop caring. 

Seriously, stop caring. 

Be Kimi Rikknen (former F1 world champ) if you have to. 

I was always hesitant to post, hesitant to share my concepts and ideas, because I was afraid of getting shot down because I wasnt cracked enough, and the simple fear: 

A high schooler building in music tech in OHIO? Whod care to listen?

Turns out people will listen as long as you have something to bring to the table, and to be honest

You will ALWAYS have something to bring to the table. 

We all have extremely unique circumstances and starting points. Its important to learn from each other, whether were in NYC, San Francisco, or yes, even Ohio. 

When we stop caring what others think, sharing our journeys authentically, there will be results. 

Guaranteed. 

It just depends on when. 

So, stop caring. 

Start sharing. 

Find your table.

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

it is with deep regret that i announce i'm quitting linkedin.


but before that i want to thank you

today marks exactly ONE month of consistency in ANYTHING in my life as of late.

over this SUPER short period of time i've:
- gotten a 100+ DMs saying my writing felt relatable and human
- gotten 200,000+ impressions and 5,000+ engagements
- grown a following of 2,000+ genuine people who chose to join along
- and somehow been named one of the fastest-growing gen-z creators on Linkedin

im proud of that. genuinely. but somewhere along the way, i started losing the plot.

i found myself drafting random posts for the sake of it, refreshing statistics minute by minute, and spending 8+ HOURS A DAY on linkedin.

my earlier goal of hitting 10k did something i didnt expect. it slowly turned you into quantification. impressions. engagement. numbers. and somewhere in that process, i started measuring my self-worth against metrics that were never meant to carry that kind of weight. realizing that brought up a quiet shame but i promised to be authentic and keep it real with you.

when i started posting, the goal was simple: connect my professional life to my real life and be honest about my self-improvement and career journey. in doing that, i didnt find "followers." i found people. thoughtful, intentional people who actually care. reducing you down to a follower count felt wrong. you arent a number. youre someone who chooses to read, respond, and show up, and that matters more to me than any stat ever could.

so im stepping away for a bit.

to sit with whats already been built, focus on college applications, and detach from the superficiality that crept in so i can come back more grounded and present. this is NOT me quitting; its me choosing what feels real.

thank you for believing in me before i fully believed in myself. thank you for proving that community still exists when you show up honestly.

ill still be writing on my substack below if you're interested.

but until then, have a nice holiday season.

peace,
aadi

aadivalappil.substack.com

ps: big thanks to Wilman Chan and Josh Freedman for being the goats for me on this journey

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

Question for the cap table architects:

Would you rather own 2% of a startup that might work?
Or 20% of the machine that builds 10 of them a year?

The first is a lottery ticket.
The second is a factory.

Most early-stage capital is allocated for the former.
Its optimized for hope.

Were building Dolos as the factory.
The model is simple:

1. Talent Engine (find the best young builders)
2. Problem Engine (source validated, niche pains)
3. Ship Engine (2-week MVP sprints)
4. Scale Engine (pour gas on what sticks)

The required check size is a fraction of a typical pre-seed.
But the required mindset is entirely different.

So, Im curious:
Are you built to back projects or systems?

12/23/25 

- Zameel
